How can I convert this console mongodb query to a C# mongo driver v2 one?

I want to create a mongodb C# driver 2 query that has the almost same result as the following mongo cli command:

db.myCollection.aggregate([{$group: { _id: null , "ids" : {$push: {$toString: "$_id"} } } }])

The output that I'm looking for is:

{ 
    "ids" : 
    [ 
        "5cde5520f838ba2b580852ca", 
        "5d3f012c555aef66082917b0", 
        "5d527092555aef4f28fee38b", 
        "5d52712f555aef4f28fee38c", 
        "5d52719e555aef4f28fee38d" 
    ] 
}

I have get this far using the Mongo's drivers overload of Linq functions

myCollection
    .AsQueryable()
    .Where(tm => tm.status == mysatus)
    .Select(tm => tm.id)

How to create a query that will be resolved on server side and not on client side?

It is not mandatory to use aggregation framework.
answer:
Thank you very much, it worked but one thing, ¿how can i make user's which don't have any balance don't show up?
Sorry i think the answer below specified that i'll try
    COALESCE(v2_wallet.amount,0)

answer: I'd be a bit surprised if the CPUs in most Casio calculators were designed with Verilog and VHDL. Python mongodb error with email as unique key

I have a collection with Username, Password and Email, so I created a unique index with pymongo in python :

import pymongo 

info.create_index( [("Username", pymongo.TEXT), ("Email", pymongo.TEXT)],unique=True)

first insert:

mydict = { "Username": "userA","Email": "emailA@example.com"}
mycol.insert_one(mydict)

second insert:

mydict = { "Username": "userB","Email": "emailB@example.com"}
mycol.insert_one(mydict)

But when I test it with a second insert it throws this exception:

pymongo.errors.DuplicateKeyError: E11000 duplicate key error collection: users.info index: Username_text_Email_text dup key: { : "com", : 0.6666666666666666 }

am I missing something here?
answer: you probably need a stable priority queue which is not common so it's not part of java collections, check this out http://stackoverflow.com/questions/21617098/making-a-java-priorityqueue-into-a-stable-priority-queue
